content:
Classic dependency-array bug. You're listing `user` as a dependency, but the effect itself updates `user` via `setUser`. So: effect runs → sets user → user changed → effect runs again → forever.

Fix: fetch when the component needs fresh data, not when `user` changes. If you just want to fetch once on mount, pass an empty array:

useEffect(() => { fetchUser().then(setUser); }, []);

If you want to refetch when some *other* value changes (like a user ID from the URL), list that instead:

useEffect(() => { fetchUser(userId).then(setUser); }, [userId]);

Yes, StrictMode intentionally calls effects twice in development to help surface bugs (setup → cleanup → setup). A naive ref guard survives because `didFetch.current` persists across the remount.

But the lesson StrictMode teaches is better: write effects that are *safe to run multiple times*. An AbortController inside the effect, cleaned up on unmount, is the idiomatic pattern:

useEffect(() => {
  const ctrl = new AbortController();
  fetch('/user', { signal: ctrl.signal }).then(setUser).catch(() => {});
  return () => ctrl.abort();
}, []);

That way double-invocation is harmless: the first fetch gets aborted, the second one completes.
